hire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1246–Male":"1246–Deceased","1290–1371":"1290–1371","–1328":"–1328","1185–1260":"1185–1260","abt 1246":"about 1246","about 1260":"about 1260","1314":"1314","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1371":"1371","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","Chillington, Stafford, england":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","of Chillington, Staff. Eng.":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Sapcote, Leicestershire, England":"Sapcote, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Chillington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","habitational name from Shilvington in Morpeth (Northumberland). The placename probably means something like ‘the farmstead of the people who live at the ledge’, from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + the groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","perhaps a habitational name from Shitlington (Yorkshire), from an Old English personal name <i>Scyt(t)el</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Giffard - Lord of Chillington was born in 1240, in Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Avice de Hastang. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Ada Basset. He died in 1314, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1246–Male":"1246–Surnud","1290–1371":"1290–1371","–1328":"–1328","1185–1260":"1185–1260","abt 1246":"umbes 1246","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1314":"1314","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1371":"1371","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","Chillington, Stafford, england":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Chillington, Staff. Eng.":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chillington, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chillington, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sapcote, Leicestershire, England":"Sapcote, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1246–Male":"1246–Kuollut","1290–1371":"1290–1371","–1328":"–1328","1185–1260":"1185–1260","abt 1246":"noin 1246","about 1260":"noin 1260","1314":"1314","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1371":